In one sense — yes.

Timing changes what transformations are available.

An acorn in one year is an acorn. In a century it may be forest soil, timber, smoke in the air, carbon in plankton, part of a fish, part of a whale. Time opens pathways that are invisible in a snapshot.

But timing alone is not enough. There is also path, constraint, and interaction.

A melody is not only notes — it is notes arranged through time. Change timing, and rhythm appears. Change rhythm, and meaning changes.

So playing in your register a bit:

Matter lends itself.
Patterns negotiate.
Time conducts.

Or shorter:

Timing is not everything.
But without timing, nothing becomes.